<section xml:id="sec-harnessinf" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Harnessing <m>\infty</m></title>

  <p> "What is the largest number you can think of?" Hopefully, you see that is a 
    question with no real answer. Maybe the closest we can come to answering that 
question is <m>\infty  \ldots</m> even though we know <m>\infty</m> is not a number. 
  </p>
<p> In fact, <m>\infty </m> is a weird creature. It breaks some of our number-intuition.
    It feels like <m>\infty</m> just does not behave. For example, can we add an infinite
    number of numbers and get something finite? We'll see that you can <m>\ldots</m> sometimes. Some of our normal addition rules act
differently when <m>\infty</m> is involved. For example, can <m>\infty</m> help us
show that <m>0 = 1 </m>? Let's start with <m>0</m>, and we know that  <m> 0 = 1 + -1 = 1 + -1 + 1 + -1.</m> 
Can't we do this forever?</p>

<p>
    <md>
      <mrow>0  \amp = (1 + -1) + (1 + -1) + 1 + \ldots </mrow>
      <mrow>   \amp =  1 + (-1 + 1) + (-1 + 1) + \ldots </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = 1 + 0 + 0 + \ldots </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp  = 1</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
<p>
   This is a problem! Apparently, the associate law of addition
   doesn't play well with <m>\infty</m>. You'll discuss this example in 
   greater detail in a later course, but this is enough to show that <m>\infty</m>
   can be very unusual.
</p>

<p>
    HILBERT HOTEL VIDEO
</p>

